Adrienne Goodson scored 17 points 
and Jennifer Azzi added 12 as the Utah Starzz avoided a
three-game losing streak with a 69-64 victory over the Charlotte Sting.
article.headline: Johnson seals win with clutch free throws
article.linkText: Sting seeing Starzz after stumbling in Utah
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY -- LaTonya Johnson shot her first free throws of the season -- with the game on the line. And she wasn't even nervous. Johnson made two fouls shots with 19.6 seconds remaining, and Adrienne Goodson scored 17 points as the Utah Starzz edged the Charlotte Sting 69-64 Saturday night. "I just really wanted to focus,'' Johnson said. "We had just been going through these situations in practice so I felt ready.'' Johnson missed the first three games of the season with a knee injury and had played just six minutes coming into Saturday's contest. But she was in the right place at the right time in this game. With the Starzz (3-2) clinging to a 63-62 lead with 21.9 seconds left, Natalie Williams missed two free throws but Johnson grabbed the long rebound. Johnson's ensuing foul shots gave Utah a 65-62 lead. "That was a huge rebound at the end of the game. Johnson came up huge for us,'' Utah coach Candi Harvey said. The Starzz held Charlotte to just one field goal over a six-minute span late in the game. Summer Erb made a baseline jumper, just the second field goal for the Sting (2-2) in the last 6:30, but the Starzz sealed the win as Goodson and Marie Ferdinand made four free throws in the last 12.8 seconds. Jennifer Azzi scored 10 of her 12 points in the second half and Margo Dydek added 11 as Utah snapped a two-game losing skid. "We made such a better effort defensively. That made the difference,'' Azzi said. Foul trouble hurt the Sting down the stretch as Charlotte Smith and Tammy Sutton-Brown both fouled out. Sutton-Brown had 14 points and 10 rebounds while Smith scored 13. The Starzz took their first lead of the game midway through the second half but the Sting responded with a 12-3 run, capped by Dawn Staley's driving lay up to put Charlotte ahead 57-49 with 6:31 to play. But the Sting had a long stretch of missed shots as the Starzz's defense increased their pressure. "Down the stretch, we didn't execute,'' Charlotte coach Anne Donovan said. "We had a seven-point lead going down the stretch and we turned the ball over too much.'' Charlotte also missed three of its last four free throws. The Starzz shot just 29 percent in the first half but trailed by just 26-24 at intermission. Game notes
Charlotte didn't attempt a single free throw in the first half, but Allison Feaster went to the line on the first possession of the second half and the Sting ended up shooting 18 free throws. ... Citing a need for more toughness, Amy Herrig started in place of 7-foot-2 Dydek at center for Utah. ... All five of Utah's games have been decided by eight points or less.
